panels.description:
Task dates of the most recent updates to each task state.

NOTE: In sandbox, we now process only a small subset of the requests, to get high throughput and test across the full date range quickly.  Cycle time is less than a day for sandbox, compared with one or two weeks for production.

panels.description:
There should generally be about 4 to 5 tasks in flight for each etl parser instance.  Currently (April 2020) there are only two instances.  

We might also want to use this internally in Gardener to determine when we should suspend operations automatically.

targets.expr: sum(gardener_tasks_in_flight{deployment=~".*universal", datatype=~"$datatypes", state="init"} > 0) # sum merges across restarts
sum by(datatype, state) (gardener_tasks_in_flight{deployment=~".*universal", datatype=~"$datatypes", state!~"init|.*Failed|complete"} > 5) # sum merges across restarts

panels.title: Tasks In Flight

panels.description:
How long each date spends in each processing state.
If Processing exceeds 12 hours, then there will likely be data loss from expiration in the task queue.

targets.expr: histogram_quantile(0.5, sum(rate(gardener_state_time_histogram_bucket{deployment=~"$deployment", deployment!~".*-universal", datatype=~"$datatypes"}[6h])) by (deployment, state, le))
histogram_quantile(0.90, sum(rate(gardener_state_time_histogram_bucket{deployment=~"$deployment", deployment!~".*-universal", datatype=~"$datatypes"}[6h])) by (deployment, state, le))

panels.title: Time in State (90th Percentile)
JSON file stats from BQ Load

panels.description:
This measures the bytes submitted for processing. 
 It reflects the ETL throughput, which is governed by the task queue rate and concurrency settings.

The rate is governed by how fast the ETL pipeline drains the task queues.  The balance across types is governed by the rate/concurrency settings on the queues.

This is fundamentally rather lumpy at the 10 minute level, so we average over an hour or more.  Aside from the fine-grained lumpiness, this should be the most stable of the throughput metrics, because it reflects the quantity of data, rather than the number or size of files.
panels.title: Byte Rate
